00:12:42.650 --> 00:12:45.110
if you get the tests
that are recommended,

00:12:45.110 --> 00:12:48.230
there's stuff you can do to
make your gut feel better,

00:12:48.230 --> 00:12:51.480
and calm down from neuropathy.

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:55.520
This also is to show that
it's not worth doing MRIs.

00:12:55.520 --> 00:12:58.310
A lot of patients with
neuropathies have MRIs.

00:12:58.310 --> 00:13:02.000
The only MRI finding here is
that this little boy's colon

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:03.200
is full of feces.

00:13:03.200 --> 00:13:05.630
Again, because he
can't move his bowels

00:13:05.630 --> 00:13:07.940
because the nerves
that control the bowels

00:13:07.940 --> 00:13:09.500
aren't working right.

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:13.130
The bones and joints, even,
are innervated by these nerves.

00:13:13.130 --> 00:13:16.550
Orthopedists, immunologists
don't think of it that much,

00:13:16.550 --> 00:13:19.040
but the bone marrow
even is densely

00:13:19.040 --> 00:13:22.490
innervated by this particular
type of small fiber nerve

00:13:22.490 --> 00:13:23.420
endings.

00:13:23.420 --> 00:13:25.460
You can see here in
one of my patients

00:13:25.460 --> 00:13:27.680
with the hereditary
neuropathy, that he's even

00:13:27.680 --> 00:13:33.310
had loss of the bones in
the ends of his fingers.

00:13:33.310 --> 00:13:35.230
In order to track
all these symptoms,

00:13:35.230 --> 00:13:37.180
there are so many
that we realized

00:13:37.180 --> 00:13:38.890
we had to develop
our questionnaire,

00:13:38.890 --> 00:13:41.990
and there was no questionnaire
anywhere in the world.

00:13:41.990 --> 00:13:45.160
And so with the help of my
former post-doctoral fellow,

00:13:45.160 --> 00:13:48.260
Roy Treister, we developed
this questionnaire.

00:13:48.260 --> 00:13:51.190
We're continuing to
improve it, right Gary?

00:13:51.190 --> 00:13:52.810
With Gary Zirpoli.

00:13:52.810 --> 00:13:54.760
But we've published
at least one paper

00:13:54.760 --> 00:13:57.430
that shows reasonable
validation,

00:13:57.430 --> 00:13:58.850
and performance of this.

00:13:58.850 --> 00:14:01.660
And these are questions--
you can't read it,

00:14:01.660 --> 00:14:05.470
but this is something that
is increasingly available.

00:14:05.470 --> 00:14:08.290
This captures the symptoms
we've heard from our patients,

00:14:08.290 --> 00:14:11.500
not just what's in the textbook.

00:14:11.500 --> 00:14:16.820
OK, so what are the tests
that can confirm small fiber?

00:14:16.820 --> 00:14:20.630
As you can see, the neuro
exam is not that sensitive,

00:14:20.630 --> 00:14:23.300
and may not pick it up.

00:14:23.300 --> 00:14:24.830
The usual tests--

00:14:24.830 --> 00:14:27.310
EMG nerve conduction
study don't detect it.

00:14:27.310 --> 00:14:30.170
Even nerve biopsies
may not pick it up.

00:14:30.170 --> 00:14:32.240
So skin biopsy is
really the test

00:14:32.240 --> 00:14:35.630
that we recommend, and again,
Heather Downs is the person who

00:14:35.630 --> 00:14:38.630
manages our skin biopsy lab.

00:14:38.630 --> 00:14:40.880
These biopsies sound
worse than they are.

00:14:40.880 --> 00:14:42.680
They're done under
local anesthesia,

00:14:42.680 --> 00:14:44.330
but they need to
be done by somebody

00:14:44.330 --> 00:14:46.430
who knows what they're doing.

00:14:46.430 --> 00:14:49.520
They can be requested to be
performed at Mass General,

00:14:49.520 --> 00:14:52.280
or a doc locally can
do them, and ship them

00:14:52.280 --> 00:14:54.680
into Mass General for analysis.

00:14:54.680 --> 00:14:57.910
Either way, the instructions
for this are on our website.

00:15:00.560 --> 00:15:03.800
Max Klein, and others from our
group, have done a lot of work

00:15:03.800 --> 00:15:07.010
on the normative data,
and these are studies that

00:15:07.010 --> 00:15:08.930
depend on normal volunteers.

00:15:08.930 --> 00:15:12.110
More than 400 of them
have come to our lab,

00:15:12.110 --> 00:15:14.960
and allowed us to remove
a tiny bit of skin,

00:15:14.960 --> 00:15:16.760
and measure the nerve endings.

00:15:16.760 --> 00:15:20.600
And I show this to you, showing
you these more than 500.

00:15:20.600 --> 00:15:23.480
What you can see is
these normal people

00:15:23.480 --> 00:15:26.510
vary a lot in the amount of
nerve endings they start with.

00:15:26.510 --> 00:15:30.920
Normal kids, the red marks here,
have far more nerve endings

00:15:30.920 --> 00:15:33.710
to begin with than
normal adults do,

00:15:33.710 --> 00:15:37.040
and the problem is is that
a lot of the commercial labs

00:15:37.040 --> 00:15:40.670
just use one threshold,
and if the count that's

00:15:40.670 --> 00:15:43.170
measured in you is above the
threshold, they say fine,

00:15:43.170 --> 00:15:44.080
you're normal.

00:15:44.080 --> 00:15:46.940
It's below the threshold, they
say oh, you've got neuropathy.

00:15:46.940 --> 00:15:48.710
But it's really much
more mathematically

00:15:48.710 --> 00:15:50.240
complex than that.

00:15:50.240 --> 00:15:53.160
We've done modeling, and so
when you have a skin biopsy

00:15:53.160 --> 00:15:56.090
please ask which lab
your biopsy is being

00:15:56.090 --> 00:15:58.220
sent to for interpretation.

00:15:58.220 --> 00:16:01.327
And for young people,
our lab is the only one

00:16:01.327 --> 00:16:03.410
that I know of anywhere
in the world with accurate

00:16:03.410 --> 00:16:06.320
norms for kids and teens.

00:16:06.320 --> 00:16:08.300
We're big fans of
physiology, which

00:16:08.300 --> 00:16:10.700
means how the nervous
system is functioning,

00:16:10.700 --> 00:16:14.060
not necessarily what it looks
like under the microscope.

00:16:14.060 --> 00:16:16.670
The test there--
autonomic function test,

00:16:16.670 --> 00:16:19.730
as far as I know, Mass
General and the Brigham

00:16:19.730 --> 00:16:23.030
are the places that offer
them here in Boston.

00:16:23.030 --> 00:16:25.580
They measure a bunch
of different aspects

00:16:25.580 --> 00:16:27.500
of nervous system
functions Sweating

00:16:27.500 --> 00:16:29.270
is particularly important.

00:16:29.270 --> 00:16:31.910
Something called the QSART,
and this person here,

00:16:31.910 --> 00:16:37.914
has loss of normal sweating
from the ends of their legs.

00:16:37.914 --> 00:16:40.580
So let's turn a little bit now--
now that you know the symptoms,

00:16:40.580 --> 00:16:42.830
and you know the
tests for neuropathy,

00:16:42.830 --> 00:16:45.350
let's turn a little bit to
some of our discoveries.

00:16:47.930 --> 00:16:50.930
Neuropathy-- anybody here who's
a physician in the audience

00:16:50.930 --> 00:16:53.270
will agree that
what we were trained

00:16:53.270 --> 00:16:55.890
is that neuropathy
affects over people.

00:16:55.890 --> 00:17:00.230
Diabetes, cancer chemotherapy,
these are the common causes.

00:17:00.230 --> 00:17:02.450
So one of the things
that's come out of our lab

00:17:02.450 --> 00:17:05.450
that I think has
been very useful

00:17:05.450 --> 00:17:08.900
is the information that
neuropathy affects kids

00:17:08.900 --> 00:17:12.230
much more often than
anybody realized.

00:17:12.230 --> 00:17:16.069
And we knew that there were
some rare genetic causes.

00:17:16.069 --> 00:17:19.970
Our lab is very interested in
genetic causes of neuropathy,

00:17:19.970 --> 00:17:24.680
and in so far as I
know, Mass General

00:17:24.680 --> 00:17:27.020
is really the place
to come for families

00:17:27.020 --> 00:17:29.990
with these kind of neuropathies.

00:17:29.990 --> 00:17:33.020
We have a Nerve Gene
Family Clinic where

00:17:33.020 --> 00:17:34.730
we can see entire families.

00:17:34.730 --> 00:17:38.420
You can see these
three very nice boys

00:17:38.420 --> 00:17:40.580
that are photographed here.

00:17:40.580 --> 00:17:44.660
We're interested in other
genetic neuropathies as well,

00:17:44.660 --> 00:17:51.050
and this shows another family
we follow that has HSAn1.

00:17:51.050 --> 00:17:55.630
Remember, I showed you the dad,
and his terrible hand up there?

00:17:55.630 --> 00:17:58.700
We're seeing his
daughters in our clinic

00:17:58.700 --> 00:18:02.270
as well with the idea of trying
to treat their neuropathy

00:18:02.270 --> 00:18:04.400
before it gets so bad.

00:18:04.400 --> 00:18:05.420
Karen, are you here?

00:18:05.420 --> 00:18:08.860
Karen Weintraub.

00:18:08.860 --> 00:18:09.640
Karen's done it.

00:18:09.640 --> 00:18:10.420
Oh, there she is.

00:18:10.420 --> 00:18:12.650
She's lurking in the back.

00:18:12.650 --> 00:18:15.220
She's got a terrific job
of helping us to bring this

00:18:15.220 --> 00:18:20.290
to awareness, and there's more
information on the Stat website

00:18:20.290 --> 00:18:22.440
if you're interested.

00:18:22.440 --> 00:18:24.650
But how about
non-genetic causes?

00:18:24.650 --> 00:18:27.740
Everything I've shown
you before is very rare.

00:18:27.740 --> 00:18:30.650
Again, kids were not thought
to have neuropathy because they

00:18:30.650 --> 00:18:33.470
don't have the medical
causes of neuropathy,

00:18:33.470 --> 00:18:37.550
and I believed the party
line until I met this college

00:18:37.550 --> 00:18:40.010
student from New
Hampshire who got

00:18:40.010 --> 00:18:43.100
admitted to Brigham with
severe pain out of nowhere.

00:18:43.100 --> 00:18:45.540
Very healthy guy, but
look at those legs.

00:18:45.540 --> 00:18:47.840
That's that
erythromelalgia again.

00:18:47.840 --> 00:18:51.270
And we figured out that in him,
it was small fiber neuropathy,

00:18:51.270 --> 00:18:54.590
but we really had no idea
why he should have it.

00:18:54.590 --> 00:18:57.110
All of his tests
came back normal.

00:18:57.110 --> 00:18:59.360
On a hunch that it
might be autoimmune,

00:18:59.360 --> 00:19:01.100
we started treating
him for that,

00:19:01.100 --> 00:19:03.770
and literally within
an hour or two,

00:19:03.770 --> 00:19:05.670
his pain started to improve.

00:19:05.670 --> 00:19:09.560
So this was truly what's
called the index case,

00:19:09.560 --> 00:19:11.750
and it changed my
career, and now

00:19:11.750 --> 00:19:14.210
look at how many other people
are hearing this story.

00:19:14.210 --> 00:19:17.570
So the importance of
one patient's story.

00:19:17.570 --> 00:19:20.250
Well, one patient is
not proof of anything,

00:19:20.250 --> 00:19:21.890
and so with Max Klein--

00:19:21.890 --> 00:19:25.670
Max, there you are,
my right hand person.

00:19:25.670 --> 00:19:29.600
We went back and looked at the
records of all the young people

00:19:29.600 --> 00:19:33.740
we'd seen with the onset of
chronic pain before age 21,

00:19:33.740 --> 00:19:35.630
and Max and I
published this paper

00:19:35.630 --> 00:19:39.920
in the Journal of Pediatrics
in 2013 that really laid out

00:19:39.920 --> 00:19:43.970
this new disease that had
never before been described.

00:19:43.970 --> 00:19:46.490
And again, you can see some
of the characteristics.

00:19:46.490 --> 00:19:50.330
3/4 of the patients
were girls or women.

00:19:50.330 --> 00:19:53.480
Some of them were grown now, but
they've had the onset of pain

00:19:53.480 --> 00:19:55.470
before age 21.

00:19:55.470 --> 00:19:57.260
And again, look at all
the different kinds

00:19:57.260 --> 00:19:58.430
of symptoms they have.

00:19:58.430 --> 00:19:59.810
You guys know all this stuff.

00:19:59.810 --> 00:20:02.360
Oh, I can skip this slide now.

00:20:02.360 --> 00:20:04.700
It just shows you that a
lot of these young people

00:20:04.700 --> 00:20:07.390
had abnormalities on
their skin biopsies,

00:20:07.390 --> 00:20:09.170
or on their autonomic
function tests.

00:20:09.170 --> 00:20:12.020
It really showed
objective evidence

00:20:12.020 --> 00:20:14.210
that they had neuropathy.

00:20:14.210 --> 00:20:16.100
So we looked at
these young people

00:20:16.100 --> 00:20:19.100
to figure out-- what
was it, 41, I think?

00:20:19.100 --> 00:20:20.720
To figure out what
the cause were,

00:20:20.720 --> 00:20:23.600
and then well, none of them
had the genetic diseases

00:20:23.600 --> 00:20:26.000
that you just heard
about, and they

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:28.790
didn't have family histories.

00:20:28.790 --> 00:20:31.370
What came out is that
although some of them

00:20:31.370 --> 00:20:35.120
were said to have psychiatric
problems, in fact,

00:20:35.120 --> 00:20:36.920
and had hospitalizations,
none of them

00:20:36.920 --> 00:20:39.390
really had serious
psych diseases.

00:20:39.390 --> 00:20:41.330
But what they did
have is a history

00:20:41.330 --> 00:20:45.830
of autoimmune illnesses, or
when your immune system begins

00:20:45.830 --> 00:20:48.200
to attack your own body.

00:20:48.200 --> 00:20:50.990
That paper was published in
the pediatric literature,

00:20:50.990 --> 00:20:53.300
but it's important
to realize that there

00:20:53.300 --> 00:20:55.280
are a lot of these
people who began

00:20:55.280 --> 00:20:58.580
to be sick during their
teen or early adult years,

00:20:58.580 --> 00:21:01.460
and they may now be in
their 40s, 50s, or 60s,

00:21:01.460 --> 00:21:04.100
and they could still
have this, and still

00:21:04.100 --> 00:21:06.320
improve with treatment.

00:21:06.320 --> 00:21:09.470
So we next started with
prospective studies,

00:21:09.470 --> 00:21:13.400
where we specifically recruited
people, and matched controls

00:21:13.400 --> 00:21:16.370
to further test this
hypothesis, and we

00:21:16.370 --> 00:21:19.580
chose to study fibromyalgia.

00:21:19.580 --> 00:21:21.410
Anybody have fibromyalgia here?

00:21:21.410 --> 00:21:23.000
Anybody been told.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:26.810
Wow, OK, so this is of interest.

00:21:26.810 --> 00:21:31.010
Fibromyalgia affects 1%
to 5% of the population

00:21:31.010 --> 00:21:35.300
in the literature, and there's
a consensus case definition,

00:21:35.300 --> 00:21:37.740
which makes it
good for research.

00:21:37.740 --> 00:21:41.060
We looked at all the different
measures of small fiber

00:21:41.060 --> 00:21:43.590
neuropathy we had
at our disposal,

00:21:43.590 --> 00:21:47.090
but we particularly prioritized
the objective test results

00:21:47.090 --> 00:21:51.320
because they can't be
faked or exaggerated,

00:21:51.320 --> 00:21:56.120
and that study showed that 40%
of the fibromyalgia patients

00:21:56.120 --> 00:21:59.900
versus only one in the
group had objective evidence

00:21:59.900 --> 00:22:01.516
of neuropathy.

00:22:01.516 --> 00:22:03.140
Kind of hard to get
that one published.

00:22:03.140 --> 00:22:05.210
What I was saying
sounded so strange

00:22:05.210 --> 00:22:09.860
because no one's really found
any biological underpinnings

00:22:09.860 --> 00:22:11.040
until then.

00:22:11.040 --> 00:22:12.860
But of course, what's
happened since is

00:22:12.860 --> 00:22:15.350
I know of more than
a dozen studies that

00:22:15.350 --> 00:22:16.760
have looked at
this, and they all

00:22:16.760 --> 00:22:18.030
are reporting the same thing.

00:22:18.030 --> 00:22:20.720
It doesn't cause
all of fibromyalgia,

00:22:20.720 --> 00:22:24.050
but what we would say
a substantial minority.

00:22:24.050 --> 00:22:26.090
And again, there
is a review article

00:22:26.090 --> 00:22:28.160
that came out in
Scientific American

00:22:28.160 --> 00:22:31.850
Mind that talks to some of
the different investigators.

00:22:31.850 --> 00:22:34.610
This study is for the
technicians in the audience,

00:22:34.610 --> 00:22:39.650
and it explains how small fiber
neuropathy can cause pain,

00:22:39.650 --> 00:22:40.970
and that it's similar.

00:22:40.970 --> 00:22:44.180
When they look and study
patients with fibromyalgia,

00:22:44.180 --> 00:22:47.360
and small fiber, they find
the same electrophysiologic

00:22:47.360 --> 00:22:50.350
abnormalities, where
these pain neurons,

00:22:50.350 --> 00:22:52.940
they're normally only
supposed to fire if somebody's

00:22:52.940 --> 00:22:54.920
sticking a knife
or a pin in you,

00:22:54.920 --> 00:22:56.750
but they're firing
spontaneously.

00:22:56.750 --> 00:22:57.920
Those nerves are active.

00:22:57.920 --> 00:23:00.470
They're sending pain
messages up to your brain,

00:23:00.470 --> 00:23:03.770
even when nothing painful is
actually happening to you,

00:23:03.770 --> 00:23:06.980
and those pain neurons
also fire excessively,

00:23:06.980 --> 00:23:09.110
and in a prolonged way.

00:23:09.110 --> 00:23:12.830
This other very technical slide
from my colleague Frank Rice

00:23:12.830 --> 00:23:17.270
from Albany shows evidence
under the microscope

00:23:17.270 --> 00:23:21.840
that the arteriovenous shunts,
again, the blood vessels,

00:23:21.840 --> 00:23:26.070
are abnormal in these
patients with fibromyalgia.

00:23:26.070 --> 00:23:29.130
And again, it's the blood
vessel abnormalities

00:23:29.130 --> 00:23:31.470
that we think underlies
some of the symptoms

00:23:31.470 --> 00:23:35.700
we see like erythromelalgia.

00:23:35.700 --> 00:23:37.560
With Max, we turned
our attention

00:23:37.560 --> 00:23:42.360
to another unexplained
similar vague illness

00:23:42.360 --> 00:23:44.440
known as Gulf War Illness.

00:23:44.440 --> 00:23:47.070
That's still a
problem now for people

00:23:47.070 --> 00:23:52.650
who were in the Gulf War in
the first and second Gulf Wars

00:23:52.650 --> 00:23:55.950
in the early 90s.

00:23:55.950 --> 00:23:57.960
We have several
grants from the DOD,

00:23:57.960 --> 00:24:01.830
and Max's study shows
strong evidence that some

00:24:01.830 --> 00:24:03.990
of the veterans--
not all of them--

00:24:03.990 --> 00:24:06.090
with Gulf War
Illness, probably have

00:24:06.090 --> 00:24:09.390
the same underlying
early onset small fiber

00:24:09.390 --> 00:24:12.600
that came on at the time
they were military recruits,

00:24:12.600 --> 00:24:16.090
and it's persisted.

00:24:16.090 --> 00:24:18.700
The next step if you're
diagnosed with neuropathy

00:24:18.700 --> 00:24:20.690
is to figure out
what the cause is,

00:24:20.690 --> 00:24:23.110
and again, indeed, there are
a lot of different underlying

00:24:23.110 --> 00:24:24.340
causes.

00:24:24.340 --> 00:24:28.420
We recommend that patients
speak with their doctor

00:24:28.420 --> 00:24:30.470
about getting these
blood tests performed.

00:24:30.470 --> 00:24:33.850
These are the ones that are
supported by published papers

00:24:33.850 --> 00:24:35.830
in the medical literature.

00:24:35.830 --> 00:24:38.960
We've looked into this
ourselves, as I'll show you.

00:24:38.960 --> 00:24:41.590
And it's really
important to figure out

00:24:41.590 --> 00:24:44.860
what the cause is in each
person so you can treat it.

00:24:44.860 --> 00:24:49.710
This blood test checklist
is available on our website.

00:24:49.710 --> 00:24:51.840
When these tests
were administered

00:24:51.840 --> 00:24:54.450
to the young people,
we didn't find evidence

00:24:54.450 --> 00:24:57.360
that they had diabetes
or heavy metal toxicity.

00:24:57.360 --> 00:24:59.430
The only thing
really that came up

00:24:59.430 --> 00:25:01.530
were blood tests
that are associated

00:25:01.530 --> 00:25:04.560
with autoimmune conditions,
and the majority

00:25:04.560 --> 00:25:06.870
of the patients, the
young onset patients,

00:25:06.870 --> 00:25:10.080
did have immune markers.

00:25:10.080 --> 00:25:13.290
When we step back to look at
the value of these blood tests

00:25:13.290 --> 00:25:18.690
in patients of all ages who have
idiopathic neuropathy-- what

00:25:18.690 --> 00:25:19.837
does idiopathic mean?

00:25:19.837 --> 00:25:21.420
It sounds like that's
the cause of it.

00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:23.370
That's the kind of
neuropathy you have.

00:25:23.370 --> 00:25:27.180
If a doctor tells you that
you have idiopathic anything,

00:25:27.180 --> 00:25:28.770
just saying no.

00:25:28.770 --> 00:25:30.720
That's not a diagnosis.

00:25:30.720 --> 00:25:35.850
Idiopathic is Latin
for we are idiots.

00:25:35.850 --> 00:25:38.730
All it means is the
doctor doesn't actually

00:25:38.730 --> 00:25:40.710
know what the cause is in you.

00:25:40.710 --> 00:25:43.860
And so they turn it into
Latin, and then the patient

00:25:43.860 --> 00:25:46.560
thinks oh, I've got
a diagnosis now.

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:49.920
I've got idiopathic neuropathy.

00:25:49.920 --> 00:25:51.000
Not so much.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:54.000
Press your doctor for
the real diagnosis.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:56.520
We looked at these
blood tests in patients

00:25:56.520 --> 00:26:02.130
with idiopathic small fiber
neuropathy, and what we found

00:26:02.130 --> 00:26:05.550
is that we could pick up an
underlying medical abnormality

00:26:05.550 --> 00:26:08.520
that could be causal in
more than half of them.

00:26:08.520 --> 00:26:12.510
Very surprisingly, it turned
out that diabetes and high blood

00:26:12.510 --> 00:26:16.410
sugar, which is said to be the
most common cause of neuropathy

00:26:16.410 --> 00:26:20.830
in the US, was not common
in this population.

00:26:20.830 --> 00:26:22.290
The reason for
that is that people

00:26:22.290 --> 00:26:24.960
who have diabetes, and who
develop burning and tingling

00:26:24.960 --> 00:26:27.570
in their feet, or
nausea, they kind of

00:26:27.570 --> 00:26:29.910
know that they have
diabetic neuropathy,

00:26:29.910 --> 00:26:32.910
and they're not
labeled as idiopathic.

00:26:32.910 --> 00:26:35.340
In fact, again,
we found evidence

00:26:35.340 --> 00:26:40.890
of unsuspected immune
blood test abnormalities.

00:26:40.890 --> 00:26:44.580
Well, all this medical
stuff and research,

00:26:44.580 --> 00:26:48.480
it's all fine and dandy, but
at the end of the day, what

00:26:48.480 --> 00:26:51.420
the patients want,
what the doctors want,

00:26:51.420 --> 00:26:55.350
what even the insurance
companies want is treatment.

00:26:55.350 --> 00:26:57.670
That's really what
it's all about.

00:26:57.670 --> 00:26:59.370
And so the
information that we've

00:26:59.370 --> 00:27:01.680
gathered from our
patients has enabled

00:27:01.680 --> 00:27:03.690
us to start treating them.

00:27:03.690 --> 00:27:06.570
In the study of
the young people,

00:27:06.570 --> 00:27:10.020
it wasn't everybody who
got immunotherapy, only 15

00:27:10.020 --> 00:27:12.150
among that very small group.

00:27:12.150 --> 00:27:15.820
The immunotherapy helped
about 80% of them.

00:27:15.820 --> 00:27:18.220
So very high level.

00:27:18.220 --> 00:27:21.780
Let's talk for a little bit more
about autoimmune neuropathy,

00:27:21.780 --> 00:27:25.410
and what this is, what this
concept is that we are really

00:27:25.410 --> 00:27:27.720
bringing to public attention.

00:27:27.720 --> 00:27:29.670
So the job of the
immune system is

00:27:29.670 --> 00:27:33.930
to protect our body from
outside invaders like the flu.

00:27:33.930 --> 00:27:38.340
I think every one of us knows
that the flu is going around.

00:27:38.340 --> 00:27:41.340
But what happens sometimes
is those immune cells

00:27:41.340 --> 00:27:43.880
can be fooled, and
mistakenly attack

00:27:43.880 --> 00:27:47.070
some of our body's
own cells, mistakenly

00:27:47.070 --> 00:27:49.210
thinking that they're invaders.

00:27:49.210 --> 00:27:50.820
And there are
autoimmune diseases

00:27:50.820 --> 00:27:53.460
that affect pretty much
every cell in our body.

00:27:53.460 --> 00:27:55.380
Everything from
rheumatoid arthritis,

00:27:55.380 --> 00:27:59.360
to multiple sclerosis,
to vitiligo, you name it,

00:27:59.360 --> 00:28:01.530
there's autoimmune diseases.

00:28:01.530 --> 00:28:04.860
Because the nerves, and the
brain, and the spinal cord

00:28:04.860 --> 00:28:07.290
are so important,
they're actually

00:28:07.290 --> 00:28:11.970
hidden behind an immunologic
barrier which protects them.

00:28:11.970 --> 00:28:15.600
But these small fibers are in
a very interesting situation.

00:28:15.600 --> 00:28:20.190
Since their job, overall, is to
help defend us against threats,

00:28:20.190 --> 00:28:22.770
they actually go
outside the walls,

00:28:22.770 --> 00:28:24.810
and they stick
their cell bodies,

00:28:24.810 --> 00:28:29.190
and they stick their distal
axons outside of the barrier,

00:28:29.190 --> 00:28:32.670
and they are so in-tune
with immune cells,

00:28:32.670 --> 00:28:35.880
they actually secrete
immune mediators,

00:28:35.880 --> 00:28:39.840
and they have physical contact
with some of the immune cells,

00:28:39.840 --> 00:28:41.670
in particular, mast cells.

00:28:41.670 --> 00:28:44.310
This shows you the
dorsal root ganglion,

00:28:44.310 --> 00:28:49.060
which is where the cell
bodies, the CPU if you will,

00:28:49.060 --> 00:28:50.880
of these small
fibers is located.

00:28:50.880 --> 00:28:54.340
And as you can see, it's
outside of the spinal cord.

00:28:54.340 --> 00:28:59.070
So not protected from
autoimmune attack.

00:28:59.070 --> 00:29:00.000
What I'm telling you--

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:03.000
I stand up here, I'm a
Harvard faculty member,

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:06.150
it makes perfect sense, but
the stuff I'm telling you

00:29:06.150 --> 00:29:08.130
is not in the medical textbooks.

00:29:10.740 --> 00:29:12.190
It's controversial.

00:29:12.190 --> 00:29:14.640
But what is it I'm
supposed to be again?

00:29:14.640 --> 00:29:15.330
Exciting?

00:29:15.330 --> 00:29:16.550
- Thrilling

00:29:16.550 --> 00:29:17.360
- Thrilling.

00:29:17.360 --> 00:29:19.680
OK, so I got to tell
you guys stuff that's

00:29:19.680 --> 00:29:24.180
not in the medical textbooks,
and you judge for yourself

00:29:24.180 --> 00:29:26.160
whether what I'm saying
make sense to you.

00:29:26.160 --> 00:29:28.590
What is in the
medical textbook now

00:29:28.590 --> 00:29:33.520
is really only two immune causes
of small fiber neuropathy,

00:29:33.520 --> 00:29:38.100
of which a rhemotologic disease
called Sjogren's is by far,

00:29:38.100 --> 00:29:39.540
the most common.

00:29:39.540 --> 00:29:43.330
The major symptoms of Sjogren's
are dry eyes or dry mouth.

00:29:43.330 --> 00:29:45.870
So if you have dry
eyes or dry mouth

00:29:45.870 --> 00:29:47.640
along with neuropathy
symptoms, it's

00:29:47.640 --> 00:29:49.660
something for you to consider.

00:29:49.660 --> 00:29:53.680
But even a lot of doctors
don't realize how common--

00:29:53.680 --> 00:29:56.950
polyneuropathy can be the
presenting symptom of Sjogren's

00:29:56.950 --> 00:29:59.020
in up to a quarter of patients.

00:29:59.020 --> 00:30:01.270
And a lot of the patients
with Sjogren's are

00:30:01.270 --> 00:30:04.000
what's called seronegative,
meaning their blood

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.370
test may not even show it.

00:30:06.370 --> 00:30:09.670
They're also very rare
immune neuropathies that

00:30:09.670 --> 00:30:11.980
are associated with cancer.

00:30:11.980 --> 00:30:14.620
But hey, in our
most recent paper,

00:30:14.620 --> 00:30:19.810
which studied 55 patients,
a quarter of them had known

00:30:19.810 --> 00:30:22.520
autoimmune diseases,
but 3/4 of them didn't.

00:30:22.520 --> 00:30:26.280
So what the heck
is going on here?

00:30:26.280 --> 00:30:30.540
Well, I think it's thrilling.

00:30:30.540 --> 00:30:32.570
I think it's thrilling
because I think we might

00:30:32.570 --> 00:30:35.570
be discovering a new disease.

00:30:35.570 --> 00:30:36.830
Maybe you guys can help.

00:30:36.830 --> 00:30:39.050
We really haven't found
a good name for this.

00:30:39.050 --> 00:30:41.660
So when we write our NIH
grants and our papers,

00:30:41.660 --> 00:30:45.060
we have to be very
conservative, and rightly so.

00:30:45.060 --> 00:30:46.940
And so what we're
calling this now

00:30:46.940 --> 00:30:52.340
is apparently autoimmune
small-fiber neuropathy.

00:30:52.340 --> 00:30:55.610
And see, I can't even say
immune because we're just

00:30:55.610 --> 00:30:57.950
starting to do the basic
science studies that

00:30:57.950 --> 00:30:59.280
are needed to prove this.

00:30:59.280 --> 00:31:01.520
So I'm calling it
apparently autoimmune,

00:31:01.520 --> 00:31:04.430
but this takes up a lot of
space when we write grants.

00:31:04.430 --> 00:31:06.710
So if anybody has a
better name, if you

00:31:06.710 --> 00:31:11.270
could come up to me afterwards,
and tell me your suggestions.

00:31:11.270 --> 00:31:14.210
And we're involved now in
a whole series of papers

00:31:14.210 --> 00:31:15.950
that we're publishing
with collaborators

00:31:15.950 --> 00:31:18.050
inside and outside of the lab.

00:31:18.050 --> 00:31:22.330
How about that
celiac paper, Maddy?

00:31:22.330 --> 00:31:23.860
You're going to do it, right?

00:31:23.860 --> 00:31:26.680
OK, I've got a commitment.

00:31:26.680 --> 00:31:31.330
Showing the overlap and
links between various types

00:31:31.330 --> 00:31:34.990
of autoimmune disease
and neuropathy.

00:31:34.990 --> 00:31:37.450
There are different kinds
of autoimmune diseases,

00:31:37.450 --> 00:31:42.910
and the evidence so far suggests
that auto antibodies may be--

00:31:42.910 --> 00:31:45.100
and B-cells, which
are made by B-cells,

00:31:45.100 --> 00:31:48.920
is probably more important
here for a bunch of reasons.

00:31:48.920 --> 00:31:52.090
You don't see a lot of cells
when you do spinal taps,

00:31:52.090 --> 00:31:54.790
or when you do biopsies
from these patients.

00:31:54.790 --> 00:31:58.570
And there also are detailed
blood test abnormalities,

00:31:58.570 --> 00:32:00.970
for instance, in the
complement pathway

00:32:00.970 --> 00:32:04.840
that are most consistent
with B-cell immune mediated

00:32:04.840 --> 00:32:06.070
dysfunction.

00:32:06.070 --> 00:32:09.430
Although, clearly when you
have longstanding cases,

00:32:09.430 --> 00:32:11.740
helper T-cells,
without any question,

00:32:11.740 --> 00:32:14.620
are involved in sustaining that.

00:32:14.620 --> 00:32:18.730
So putting this all together,
again, treatment is our focus.

00:32:18.730 --> 00:32:24.520
Our most recent paper reported
on the first ever study

00:32:24.520 --> 00:32:29.320
of immunotherapy for apparently
autoimmune small-fiber

00:32:29.320 --> 00:32:30.980
neuropathy.

00:32:30.980 --> 00:32:34.180
This is a retrospective study.

00:32:34.180 --> 00:32:36.460
Meaning it's a look
back at patients

00:32:36.460 --> 00:32:38.050
who were already treated.

00:32:38.050 --> 00:32:40.780
It's not the so-called
gold standard,

00:32:40.780 --> 00:32:44.960
the placebo controlled
randomized trial.

00:32:44.960 --> 00:32:46.870
The reason for that
is because those

00:32:46.870 --> 00:32:48.820
costs millions and
millions of dollars,

00:32:48.820 --> 00:32:51.760
and you've got to get
the money from NIH

00:32:51.760 --> 00:32:55.360
or other similar funding
agency, and the problem

00:32:55.360 --> 00:32:59.290
is they are not going to give
you the taxpayers' money to do

00:32:59.290 --> 00:33:02.260
this kind of study unless
there is some published

00:33:02.260 --> 00:33:04.720
evidence in the literature
that you're barking up

00:33:04.720 --> 00:33:06.820
the right tree, and
not the wrong tree.

00:33:06.820 --> 00:33:09.070
So we've now published
the paper that I

00:33:09.070 --> 00:33:11.020
think shows some
evidence that it

00:33:11.020 --> 00:33:13.900
might be reasonable to
consider these kinds of trials.

00:33:13.900 --> 00:33:18.100
This is what's called a proof
of concept research publication.

00:33:18.100 --> 00:33:22.070
This was done with my former
post-doctoral fellow, Doctor

00:33:22.070 --> 00:33:25.810
Liu, and we looked
back, again, at patients

00:33:25.810 --> 00:33:29.290
who had received a particular
treatment called IVIg, which

00:33:29.290 --> 00:33:31.360
is the best treatment
for other types

00:33:31.360 --> 00:33:33.940
of autoimmune neuropathies.

00:33:33.940 --> 00:33:36.880
So we had given it to
some of our patients here.

00:33:36.880 --> 00:33:39.160
We selected them
very rigorously.

00:33:39.160 --> 00:33:41.800
We do not want to give these
treatments to people who have

00:33:41.800 --> 00:33:43.510
other causes of neuropathy.

00:33:43.510 --> 00:33:46.270
That wouldn't work, and it would
be a lot of time, and effort,

00:33:46.270 --> 00:33:47.240
and wasted money.

00:33:47.240 --> 00:33:50.350
These are very expensive
treatments, I should mention.

00:33:50.350 --> 00:33:52.140
We tracked how patients did.

00:33:52.140 --> 00:33:55.450
The symptom important to a
lot of patients was pain.

00:33:55.450 --> 00:33:57.490
We tracked objective
measurements

00:33:57.490 --> 00:34:00.700
from AFT, autonomic
function testing.

00:34:00.700 --> 00:34:03.890
The difference in AFT
results is shown here.

00:34:03.890 --> 00:34:07.030
The blue are the
abnormal ATFT results

00:34:07.030 --> 00:34:08.770
before going on this treatment.

00:34:08.770 --> 00:34:10.380
The red is after.

00:34:10.380 --> 00:34:14.670
So 93% had abnormal results
before starting the treatment.

00:34:14.670 --> 00:34:19.540
54% had abnormal
results after treatment,

00:34:19.540 --> 00:34:23.770
and the adverse events
were pretty similar

00:34:23.770 --> 00:34:27.452
in other illnesses.

00:34:27.452 --> 00:34:31.510
So we're building on something
that we call a small fiber

00:34:31.510 --> 00:34:34.630
registry, and what a
registry is, is it's

00:34:34.630 --> 00:34:37.000
when you go to a
doc, and they really

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:39.489
try to track the information
they get from you,

00:34:39.489 --> 00:34:43.719
and they try to collect the
information in a standard way.

00:34:43.719 --> 00:34:46.810
And it's a heck of a lot
of effort to develop this.

00:34:46.810 --> 00:34:50.380
Again, it's not something
that is grant funded,

00:34:50.380 --> 00:34:52.750
but you kind of need it
in order to do research.

00:34:52.750 --> 00:34:55.294
And yeah, I'm looking at the
epidemiologists in the audience

00:34:55.294 --> 00:34:55.960
who would agree.

00:34:55.960 --> 00:34:58.870
Any other epidemiologists
here, by the way?

00:34:58.870 --> 00:35:01.300
Yeah, OK, so I've got
to just look at you two.

00:35:01.300 --> 00:35:04.240
And this just shows you some
of the types of information

00:35:04.240 --> 00:35:05.410
that we have.

00:35:05.410 --> 00:35:10.460
We're very interested and very
bullish on the blood samples,

00:35:10.460 --> 00:35:13.180
and if any of my patients are
here who've donated our blood,

00:35:13.180 --> 00:35:15.820
we're incredibly grateful
to you because this

00:35:15.820 --> 00:35:21.190
is a tremendous resource
for future research.

00:35:21.190 --> 00:35:24.280
This goes to show you some
of the kinds of experiments

00:35:24.280 --> 00:35:26.170
that we do with this blood.

00:35:26.170 --> 00:35:29.140
I think the most important
experiments, overall,

00:35:29.140 --> 00:35:31.180
are the ones that
involve something

00:35:31.180 --> 00:35:33.280
called passive transfer.

00:35:33.280 --> 00:35:36.130
And this is what's
used to really prove

00:35:36.130 --> 00:35:38.810
whether a disease is
autoimmune or not,

00:35:38.810 --> 00:35:42.610
and it involves taking a frozen
sample of that patient's blood.

00:35:42.610 --> 00:35:45.940
We're able to take extracts
of that patient's blood,

00:35:45.940 --> 00:35:48.460
and inject it into
little lab animals,

00:35:48.460 --> 00:35:52.510
and then see whether
those mice or rats develop

00:35:52.510 --> 00:35:54.490
symptoms of neuropathy.

00:35:54.490 --> 00:35:57.790
And if we do, that's something
that we can capture in our lab

00:35:57.790 --> 00:36:02.290
as well, and that provides
proof that in that patient,

00:36:02.290 --> 00:36:05.560
they have an autoimmune cause,
or something in their blood

00:36:05.560 --> 00:36:08.090
that's causing their neuropathy.

00:36:08.090 --> 00:36:10.300
This kind of research is
being done more and more

00:36:10.300 --> 00:36:14.110
in the cancer field, where
patient's own samples are used

00:36:14.110 --> 00:36:18.400
to create individual mice or
rats that then can be used

00:36:18.400 --> 00:36:21.220
to test the effects of
specific treatments,

00:36:21.220 --> 00:36:23.260
like specific chemotherapy--

00:36:23.260 --> 00:36:25.160
what's going to work
in that patient.

00:36:25.160 --> 00:36:27.850
So this is a very
powerful technique.

00:36:27.850 --> 00:36:29.980
And what you can
see here is the rat

00:36:29.980 --> 00:36:33.997
that was injected with
blood from the patient shown

00:36:33.997 --> 00:36:34.580
on the bottom.

00:36:34.580 --> 00:36:37.360
It's the serum from the
blood, not all the blood.

00:36:37.360 --> 00:36:39.600
Developed some
behavioral abnormalities,

00:36:39.600 --> 00:36:43.660
some signs of pain in the
paw of that particular rat.

00:36:43.660 --> 00:36:46.240
Whereas another
rat, shown in blue,

00:36:46.240 --> 00:36:48.460
maintained normal
sensory functions.

00:36:48.460 --> 00:36:50.860
So again, we're going
to see differences

00:36:50.860 --> 00:36:53.500
in the different animals,
depending on which

00:36:53.500 --> 00:36:56.620
patient serum was used.

00:36:56.620 --> 00:36:59.470
We're also developing
standardized exam forms,

00:36:59.470 --> 00:37:03.210
and that's a project in
particular of Shawn Downs--

00:37:03.210 --> 00:37:07.300
there you go-- with the
guidance of Gary Zirpoli,

00:37:07.300 --> 00:37:10.060
and this allows us
to figure out which

00:37:10.060 --> 00:37:15.250
aspects that become abnormal
are most useful for diagnosing

00:37:15.250 --> 00:37:16.240
neuropathy.

00:37:16.240 --> 00:37:18.100
And all these tests
I'm telling you about,

00:37:18.100 --> 00:37:21.190
all these fancy tests, is
wonderful for the people who

00:37:21.190 --> 00:37:23.110
can come and get
them, but we're well

00:37:23.110 --> 00:37:27.190
aware that 99.9% of
the people in the world

00:37:27.190 --> 00:37:30.340
can't come here to
Cambridge, and Boston,

00:37:30.340 --> 00:37:33.920
or similar universities to
have these kinds of tests.

00:37:33.920 --> 00:37:36.490
So what we're trying
to do is we ask

00:37:36.490 --> 00:37:41.260
the people who are coming
for these fancy shmancy tests

00:37:41.260 --> 00:37:45.190
to also see if they're
willing to let us take

00:37:45.190 --> 00:37:50.260
a few noninvasive simple tests,
and see how the results of that

00:37:50.260 --> 00:37:51.490
correlate.

00:37:51.490 --> 00:37:54.910
The idea is that if we can
develop simple, easy, cheap

00:37:54.910 --> 00:37:57.880
tests, and show that
they work almost as

00:37:57.880 --> 00:38:00.580
well as the
expensive tests, then

00:38:00.580 --> 00:38:03.550
they might be able to be
used all around the world.

00:38:03.550 --> 00:38:06.070
And with Max, who's
an engineer, and some

00:38:06.070 --> 00:38:10.060
of our other collaborators,
and Dr. Serrador from Rutgers,

00:38:10.060 --> 00:38:13.990
we're looking at the pupil
responses in the eye.

00:38:13.990 --> 00:38:16.930
The eye is a window
to the nervous system.

00:38:16.930 --> 00:38:19.030
Some people say the eyes
the window to the soul,

00:38:19.030 --> 00:38:21.790
but I prefer to think of
it as to the nervous system

00:38:21.790 --> 00:38:23.950
because those same
nerves control

00:38:23.950 --> 00:38:25.780
the functions of your eye.

00:38:25.780 --> 00:38:29.530
And so you can see this eye
from one of my young patients

00:38:29.530 --> 00:38:30.610
is very dilated.

00:38:30.610 --> 00:38:32.770
Her pupil is very dilated.

00:38:32.770 --> 00:38:35.560
With these pupil
metric goggles, what

00:38:35.560 --> 00:38:38.020
we're able to do in
our lab is to measure

00:38:38.020 --> 00:38:41.470
these pupillary
reflexes, record them,

00:38:41.470 --> 00:38:43.840
to test whether these
are useful things.

00:38:43.840 --> 00:38:46.150
If it turns out
to be useful, it's

00:38:46.150 --> 00:38:49.060
something that could
be very widely used.

00:38:49.060 --> 00:38:50.470
For instance,
perhaps, maybe it's

00:38:50.470 --> 00:38:53.560
something that could
be put on a cell phone.

00:38:53.560 --> 00:38:57.260
There aren't any biotech
entrepreneurs here, are there?

00:38:57.260 --> 00:38:59.190
Just checking.

00:38:59.190 --> 00:39:01.660
That's proprietary.

00:39:01.660 --> 00:39:07.800
So I'm going to wrap up by
stepping back, and bringing

00:39:07.800 --> 00:39:10.440
this up to think
well, I've told you

00:39:10.440 --> 00:39:12.540
about rare genetic diseases.

00:39:12.540 --> 00:39:15.300
I've told you about
common diseases, diabetes,

00:39:15.300 --> 00:39:18.690
a lot of different
causes of neuropathy.

00:39:18.690 --> 00:39:21.030
How big is this problem, anyway?

00:39:21.030 --> 00:39:22.590
Well, here's a clue.

00:39:22.590 --> 00:39:26.390
This is the epidemics
lecture series.

00:39:26.390 --> 00:39:29.070
So I've run some sort
of hand-waving thought

00:39:29.070 --> 00:39:29.760
experiments.

00:39:29.760 --> 00:39:31.020
No one knows the numbers.

00:39:31.020 --> 00:39:33.370
No one knows the
right answer here,

00:39:33.370 --> 00:39:35.670
but if you look back at
what's been published,

00:39:35.670 --> 00:39:38.160
there's really only
one epidemiologic study

00:39:38.160 --> 00:39:40.410
so far out of the Netherlands.

00:39:40.410 --> 00:39:42.990
And if you apply the numbers
they got to the world

00:39:42.990 --> 00:39:47.610
population, it suggests there
might be four million cases

00:39:47.610 --> 00:39:49.215
of small fiber in the world.

00:39:49.215 --> 00:39:51.600
The only problem with
that is for that study,

00:39:51.600 --> 00:39:56.160
you had to have a physician
verified objective diagnosis,

00:39:56.160 --> 00:39:58.830
and what I've been telling
you is that more than 90%

00:39:58.830 --> 00:40:01.110
of the people don't even
know they have this disease,

00:40:01.110 --> 00:40:03.600
and they've never even
seen a neurologist.

00:40:03.600 --> 00:40:07.560
So it may be that there's
closer to 40 million cases

00:40:07.560 --> 00:40:10.230
in the world than four million.

00:40:10.230 --> 00:40:13.020
But here's another way
you could look at it.

00:40:13.020 --> 00:40:15.300
Fibromyalgia effects
several percent

00:40:15.300 --> 00:40:17.220
of the world's population.

00:40:17.220 --> 00:40:20.130
Given that a dozen labs
are pretty much showing

00:40:20.130 --> 00:40:25.110
that maybe 40% of these may
have small fiber neuropathy,

00:40:25.110 --> 00:40:27.360
well, then that yields
the idea that there

00:40:27.360 --> 00:40:31.470
may be 75 million fibromyalgia
patients around the world who

00:40:31.470 --> 00:40:35.700
could have small fiber, but
not all small fiber patients

00:40:35.700 --> 00:40:38.230
have been diagnosed
with fibromyalgia.

00:40:38.230 --> 00:40:40.660
So when you go back, and
you factor the rest of them

00:40:40.660 --> 00:40:46.460
then, well, now you're
starting to look at numbers

00:40:46.460 --> 00:40:48.680
in the hundreds of millions.

00:40:48.680 --> 00:40:50.780
And again, I'm not
saying that that's

00:40:50.780 --> 00:40:51.980
how many people have this.

00:40:51.980 --> 00:40:53.300
We really don't know.

00:40:53.300 --> 00:40:55.640
The information
just isn't there.

00:40:55.640 --> 00:41:00.680
But whether it's 40 million,
four million, 400 million,

00:41:00.680 --> 00:41:02.780
either way, this told
us we need to start

00:41:02.780 --> 00:41:06.470
looking at this at the
population level, not only just

00:41:06.470 --> 00:41:10.100
with the individual patients
that make it into my office.

00:41:10.100 --> 00:41:12.680
And so for that reason,
we're collaborating

00:41:12.680 --> 00:41:14.750
with epidemiologists
at the Harvard

00:41:14.750 --> 00:41:16.610
School of Public Health.

00:41:16.610 --> 00:41:20.510
And Gary and I, with
our collaborators,

00:41:20.510 --> 00:41:25.220
are getting ready to publish the
first ever epidemiologic study.

00:41:25.220 --> 00:41:27.770
Now, this is all peripheral
neuropathy, not just

00:41:27.770 --> 00:41:29.720
small fiber neuropathy.

00:41:29.720 --> 00:41:32.450
In the US, and this is
through the Nurses' Health

00:41:32.450 --> 00:41:35.720
Study 2, which has
been tracking over

00:41:35.720 --> 00:41:39.690
100,000 nurses all across
the US for decades,

00:41:39.690 --> 00:41:42.190
and we have impeccable
information about their health

00:41:42.190 --> 00:41:44.940
care records, which
one has diabetes, which

00:41:44.940 --> 00:41:46.970
one was treated for
cancer, what drugs

00:41:46.970 --> 00:41:48.990
were used in many of them.

00:41:48.990 --> 00:41:52.670
And we've been able to pick
out more than 3,000 people who

00:41:52.670 --> 00:41:55.010
say, yeah, my doc
has told me that I've

00:41:55.010 --> 00:41:56.900
got peripheral neuropathy.

00:41:56.900 --> 00:42:00.080
So by going, and sending out
special additional surveys

00:42:00.080 --> 00:42:02.450
to them, we
anticipate that we're

00:42:02.450 --> 00:42:06.050
going to be able to learn more
about peripheral neuropathy

00:42:06.050 --> 00:42:09.260
than has ever been known
anywhere in the world.

00:42:09.260 --> 00:42:13.120
That's the power
of epidemiology.

00:42:13.120 --> 00:42:16.090
OK, so to allow
time for questions,

00:42:16.090 --> 00:42:18.340
I'm going to give you
a small summary first,

00:42:18.340 --> 00:42:21.190
and then we're going to move
into the question period.

00:42:21.190 --> 00:42:25.030
So I'm going to give you a
small summary of a big topic.

00:42:25.030 --> 00:42:28.360
That the symptoms of
small fiber neuropathy

00:42:28.360 --> 00:42:32.020
include pain and itch,
fatigue, [INAUDIBLE],,

00:42:32.020 --> 00:42:35.170
things that people don't
associate with neuropathy.

00:42:35.170 --> 00:42:38.260
I've told you what some of the
recommended diagnostic tests

00:42:38.260 --> 00:42:39.240
are.

00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:42.190
That blood tests are very
useful in identifying--

00:42:42.190 --> 00:42:45.100
not in everybody, but in
the majority of people,

00:42:45.100 --> 00:42:48.100
in providing hints as to
what the cause might be.

00:42:48.100 --> 00:42:50.830
Sometimes the tests need to
be repeated more than once,

00:42:50.830 --> 00:42:54.040
or some people may need
specialized genetic tests,

00:42:54.040 --> 00:42:57.550
or other special tests to
figure out what's going on.

00:42:57.550 --> 00:43:00.910
That there's strong evidence
from labs all around the world

00:43:00.910 --> 00:43:10.720
that patients who have,
whether it's CME, CFS, Gulf War

00:43:10.720 --> 00:43:15.310
Illness, chronic Lyme, that
a substantial proportion--

00:43:15.310 --> 00:43:18.610
somewhere between a third to
a half of people who receive

00:43:18.610 --> 00:43:22.630
these labels may in fact,
have an actual underlying,

00:43:22.630 --> 00:43:25.490
potentially treatable
medical disease.

00:43:25.490 --> 00:43:28.540
So that's maybe the single
most important message,

00:43:28.540 --> 00:43:30.460
is to take this information out.

00:43:30.460 --> 00:43:33.280
Every one of us, I think,
has family members or friends

00:43:33.280 --> 00:43:35.410
who are suffering
from these illnesses.

00:43:35.410 --> 00:43:37.090
It's really important
that they know

00:43:37.090 --> 00:43:40.630
that they can ask their doctor
have we thought about this?

00:43:40.630 --> 00:43:44.540
Would it be reasonable to think
about testing me for this?

00:43:44.540 --> 00:43:47.630
Some of the patients with
this type of neuropathy

00:43:47.630 --> 00:43:51.110
probably have immune
causes, and in them,

00:43:51.110 --> 00:43:53.780
the treatments for other
immune neuropathies

00:43:53.780 --> 00:43:59.060
are quite reasonably safe,
and appear to be effective.

00:43:59.060 --> 00:44:00.620
We don't know the
numbers of people

00:44:00.620 --> 00:44:02.930
who have this around the
world, but either way, it's

00:44:02.930 --> 00:44:03.920
a heck of a lot.

00:44:03.920 --> 00:44:06.140
Either way it's too many.

00:44:06.140 --> 00:44:10.010
And my point is is let's
step away from this whole

00:44:10.010 --> 00:44:14.460
opioid crisis business, and
giving people painkillers.

00:44:14.460 --> 00:44:16.910
I've got nothing
against painkillers,

00:44:16.910 --> 00:44:19.470
but we're so much
smarter than that now,

00:44:19.470 --> 00:44:21.170
and we can find
better treatments.

00:44:21.170 --> 00:44:25.970
Treatments that actually fight
back at the disease, not just

00:44:25.970 --> 00:44:28.040
masking the pain
that you have to take

00:44:28.040 --> 00:44:30.020
for decade after decade.

00:44:30.020 --> 00:44:34.700
So let's move onto the era
of smart medicine treatment.

