00:51:20.780 --> 00:51:23.540
And the second question was
about when we mentioned--

00:51:23.540 --> 00:51:24.665
- Wait, the first question.

00:51:24.665 --> 00:51:25.970
- Oh, sorry.

00:51:25.970 --> 00:51:28.290
- Let me just answer the
first question first.

00:51:28.290 --> 00:51:30.500
So the question is
about skin biopsies,

00:51:30.500 --> 00:51:34.820
and that's currently
the best test available,

00:51:34.820 --> 00:51:36.390
but it's far from perfect.

00:51:36.390 --> 00:51:40.280
There's no medical test
that's 100% perfect.

00:51:40.280 --> 00:51:42.530
And so what I would
say if the skin biopsy

00:51:42.530 --> 00:51:45.500
shows that you have
severe nerve damage,

00:51:45.500 --> 00:51:48.770
then it's highly
likely that you do

00:51:48.770 --> 00:51:50.270
have this kind of neuropathy.

00:51:50.270 --> 00:51:53.150
That's called positive
predictive value.

00:51:53.150 --> 00:51:55.730
But on the other hand, it
doesn't always pick it up.

00:51:55.730 --> 00:51:58.700
As you say, what if the biopsy
is done early in the course?

00:51:58.700 --> 00:52:01.620
Or what if it's taken from
the wrong part of the body?

00:52:01.620 --> 00:52:04.430
So the fact that you
have a normal skin biopsy

00:52:04.430 --> 00:52:07.280
doesn't mean you don't have
this kind of neuropathy.

00:52:07.280 --> 00:52:09.560
It makes it less likely.

00:52:09.560 --> 00:52:11.930
And some patients I've
been following for years,

00:52:11.930 --> 00:52:14.780
their skin biopsies were
normal at the beginning,

00:52:14.780 --> 00:52:16.910
we would suggest they
might want to repeat it

00:52:16.910 --> 00:52:20.900
a few years later if we still
didn't know what was going on.

00:52:20.900 --> 00:52:24.110
And in some of them, it's
dropped over the years.

00:52:24.110 --> 00:52:25.890
It might still be
in the normal range,

00:52:25.890 --> 00:52:29.300
but it might have started out
at the 70 or 80th percentile,

00:52:29.300 --> 00:52:32.600
and it's dropped 60, 40, 20.

00:52:32.600 --> 00:52:37.490
So that tells us their nerves
are going, or not healthy,

00:52:37.490 --> 00:52:39.980
or it drops into
the abnormal range.

00:52:39.980 --> 00:52:45.490
So they're not perfect, but
it's still very important.

00:52:45.490 --> 00:52:47.335
It's a very important,
very useful test.

00:52:47.335 --> 00:52:48.751
And what was your
second question?

00:52:48.751 --> 00:52:51.310
The second question
is about Sjogren's.

00:52:51.310 --> 00:52:54.280
You mentioned that a lot of
patients are seronegative.

00:52:54.280 --> 00:52:56.800
How do you correlate
patients who

00:52:56.800 --> 00:53:01.150
might have the autonomic testing
showing positive, and the sweat

00:53:01.150 --> 00:53:03.760
testing, but then
they're seronegative?

00:53:03.760 --> 00:53:04.750
What is the next steps?

00:53:04.750 --> 00:53:09.030
And they do have--
they're very symptomatic.

00:53:09.030 --> 00:53:11.640
- That's kind of a complicated
question because the sweat

00:53:11.640 --> 00:53:15.690
testing isn't the recommended
test for diagnosing Sjogren's.

00:53:15.690 --> 00:53:19.230
So Sjogren's requires a
rheumatology evaluation

00:53:19.230 --> 00:53:21.790
by somebody who's
really familiar with it.

00:53:21.790 --> 00:53:24.510
They factor in a lot of
things-- the symptoms you have,

00:53:24.510 --> 00:53:28.060
looking in the eyes, their
formal diagnostic criteria.

00:53:28.060 --> 00:53:30.330
Sometimes they take
a biopsy from the lip

00:53:30.330 --> 00:53:32.370
to look at the
salivary glands, and it

00:53:32.370 --> 00:53:36.820
can take a few years to work
out a Sjogren's diagnosis.

00:53:36.820 --> 00:53:39.660
Shall we work our way towards
some of the patient people?

00:53:39.660 --> 00:53:41.190
We can come back
to the back, but I

00:53:41.190 --> 00:53:45.150
want to also get some equal
representation from the front.

00:53:45.150 --> 00:53:49.160
- Hi, I'm a patient, and I
just want to understand better

00:53:49.160 --> 00:53:50.160
the impact on the brain.

00:53:50.160 --> 00:53:52.421
- Could you raise
your hand again?

00:53:52.421 --> 00:53:52.920
Oh, great.

00:53:52.920 --> 00:53:53.940
Thank you, OK.

00:53:53.940 --> 00:53:56.670
- I'd like to understand
better the impacts

00:53:56.670 --> 00:53:58.090
on the brain both ways.

00:53:58.090 --> 00:54:00.420
One of your slides
mentioned polypharmacy

00:54:00.420 --> 00:54:02.254
as a potential cause.

00:54:02.254 --> 00:54:04.170
So I don't know if that's
too many medications

00:54:04.170 --> 00:54:05.160
impacting the brain.

00:54:05.160 --> 00:54:09.660
And then also, could occipital
neuralgia be a headache caused

00:54:09.660 --> 00:54:12.730
by small fiber neuropathy?

00:54:12.730 --> 00:54:14.780
- That's a whole complex topic.

00:54:14.780 --> 00:54:16.420
I don't know if any one--

00:54:16.420 --> 00:54:20.170
I'm a neuroscientist, and I'm
in the neurology department.

00:54:20.170 --> 00:54:23.280
I'm surrounded by experts
on cognitive function,

00:54:23.280 --> 00:54:25.060
by experts on
headache, and I don't

00:54:25.060 --> 00:54:27.190
know of any of them that's
looking at small fiber

00:54:27.190 --> 00:54:28.660
neuropathy yet.

00:54:28.660 --> 00:54:30.250
So another one of my goals--

00:54:30.250 --> 00:54:33.220
I hope I have some colleagues,
and fellow researchers

00:54:33.220 --> 00:54:34.580
in the audience.

00:54:34.580 --> 00:54:36.250
Another reason to
give this talk is

00:54:36.250 --> 00:54:38.920
to excite people who are
working in different areas

00:54:38.920 --> 00:54:41.530
to start taking up
their own projects.

00:54:41.530 --> 00:54:45.560
We'd be thrilled to have
experts start to look at this.

00:54:45.560 --> 00:54:48.670
What I tried to summarize
in that complicated slide

00:54:48.670 --> 00:54:52.930
is that peripheral neuropathy,
specifically small fiber,

00:54:52.930 --> 00:54:56.690
can affect the brain in
a lot of different ways.

00:54:56.690 --> 00:54:59.740
For one thing, those cells, we
think of them as peripheral,

00:54:59.740 --> 00:55:02.470
but they actually send
part of their cell up

00:55:02.470 --> 00:55:04.100
into the spinal cord.

00:55:04.100 --> 00:55:06.820
So it's part of the central
nervous system, as well as

00:55:06.820 --> 00:55:10.310
the peripheral nervous system.

00:55:10.310 --> 00:55:14.230
Even the ones that don't send
an axon up the spinal cord,

00:55:14.230 --> 00:55:17.390
but that end where they
come into the spinal cord,

00:55:17.390 --> 00:55:18.610
they synapse.

00:55:18.610 --> 00:55:20.510
They connect with
other nerve cells.

00:55:20.510 --> 00:55:23.170
So there are
tran-synaptic effects.

00:55:23.170 --> 00:55:24.850
And then there are
network effects

00:55:24.850 --> 00:55:28.360
in the brain when the brain
cells change their function,

00:55:28.360 --> 00:55:32.050
for instance, because of
reduced sensory input coming in.

00:55:32.050 --> 00:55:33.970
And then what you
mentioned is what

00:55:33.970 --> 00:55:37.840
I call the downward spiral,
which was when people are sick,

00:55:37.840 --> 00:55:39.340
and they don't know
what's going on,

00:55:39.340 --> 00:55:41.350
and they're doing
all this stuff,

00:55:41.350 --> 00:55:44.110
and they get on medication
for this for their stomach,

00:55:44.110 --> 00:55:46.570
for their pain, they
become depressed,

00:55:46.570 --> 00:55:48.730
they become inactive.

00:55:48.730 --> 00:55:51.620
All of these things have
effects on the brain as well,

00:55:51.620 --> 00:55:55.030
and so those really are
tertiary and quaternary

00:55:55.030 --> 00:55:57.190
effects of being so sick.

00:55:57.190 --> 00:56:00.703
So it affects the brain at
a lot of different levels.

00:56:00.703 --> 00:56:01.669
- Thank you.

00:56:10.380 --> 00:56:15.660
- Hi, I was asking about
ESR because you used that

00:56:15.660 --> 00:56:19.710
as one of your
tests, and I've heard

00:56:19.710 --> 00:56:22.230
that it's kind of unreliable,
and I was wondering

00:56:22.230 --> 00:56:24.060
what sort of ranges
you're looking at,

00:56:24.060 --> 00:56:28.490
and why you chose that test.

00:56:28.490 --> 00:56:33.380
- We actually don't rely on
any one test of autoimmunity.

00:56:33.380 --> 00:56:36.860
It's not a black or a
white situation for exactly

00:56:36.860 --> 00:56:39.440
the reason that you
point out, which

00:56:39.440 --> 00:56:44.010
is that these tests that are
used to track immune function,

00:56:44.010 --> 00:56:48.380
I wouldn't call them unreliable,
but I'd call them nonspecific.

00:56:48.380 --> 00:56:51.170
And so that means they
don't correlate that well.

00:56:51.170 --> 00:56:53.240
Somebody could have
an autoimmune disease,

00:56:53.240 --> 00:56:54.920
and have a normal blood test.

00:56:54.920 --> 00:56:58.040
A certain number of people have
abnormal blood test results,

00:56:58.040 --> 00:57:00.660
and they don't have
autoimmune diseases.

00:57:00.660 --> 00:57:03.110
So they're statistically
associated,

00:57:03.110 --> 00:57:05.690
but it's not a black
or white relationship,

00:57:05.690 --> 00:57:08.960
and that's why I mentioned
these things like--

00:57:08.960 --> 00:57:10.870
I don't remember
the exact percent

00:57:10.870 --> 00:57:14.910
have abnormal ESR, which stands
for erythrocyte sedimentation

00:57:14.910 --> 00:57:15.410
rate.

00:57:15.410 --> 00:57:17.930
Others may have
a low complement.

00:57:17.930 --> 00:57:22.340
Others may have a test called
ANA, anti-nuclear antibodies.

00:57:22.340 --> 00:57:25.850
And again, none of these are
specific for small fiber,

00:57:25.850 --> 00:57:28.220
or any particular
disease at all,

00:57:28.220 --> 00:57:32.630
but together, they kind
of give a hint, a clue,

00:57:32.630 --> 00:57:36.500
when they're elevated in such
a high percentage of patients

00:57:36.500 --> 00:57:38.690
that there may be a
link to an autoimmunity.

00:57:38.690 --> 00:57:40.116
Not in each person.

00:57:49.540 --> 00:57:52.330
- Hi, thank you for the talk.

00:57:52.330 --> 00:57:56.770
I wanted to ask-- you mentioned
CFS or chronic fatigue,

00:57:56.770 --> 00:58:01.030
and it's one of these
idiopathic things that

00:58:01.030 --> 00:58:05.140
might have small fiber
neuropathy as the underlying

00:58:05.140 --> 00:58:06.130
cause.

00:58:06.130 --> 00:58:11.280
What sort of work has your
group or others done on that?

00:58:11.280 --> 00:58:14.470
- My collaboration with
David Systrom and his team

00:58:14.470 --> 00:58:15.970
at the Brigham,
I think, is going

00:58:15.970 --> 00:58:19.330
to publish some really exciting
data coming out of that,

00:58:19.330 --> 00:58:21.130
and I think it's OK
for me to mention it

00:58:21.130 --> 00:58:26.160
since we've already published
it in preliminary abstract form.

00:58:26.160 --> 00:58:33.850
And what that's going to show
is that a substantial percent

00:58:33.850 --> 00:58:35.680
of people who present--

00:58:35.680 --> 00:58:36.970
he's not a neurologist.

00:58:36.970 --> 00:58:38.360
He's not a nerve doc.

00:58:38.360 --> 00:58:41.980
He's a lung and circulation doc.

00:58:41.980 --> 00:58:46.060
People who go to him because of
this lack of energy, and just

00:58:46.060 --> 00:58:48.730
difficulty getting out
of bed, and inability

00:58:48.730 --> 00:58:52.550
to do their routine, a
substantial percent of them do,

00:58:52.550 --> 00:58:55.180
in fact, have this kind
of peripheral neuropathy.

00:58:55.180 --> 00:58:59.110
So not everybody, but enough
that a doctor should always

00:58:59.110 --> 00:59:03.380
think about it as part of
their differential diagnosis.

00:59:03.380 --> 00:59:04.640
And it's treatable.

00:59:04.640 --> 00:59:06.822
Once you know-- there
are many reasons not

00:59:06.822 --> 00:59:08.030
to be able to get out of bed.

00:59:08.030 --> 00:59:10.800
Depression, for instance,
is a very common one.

00:59:10.800 --> 00:59:14.790
So it's important to go beyond
the I have chronic fatigue,

00:59:14.790 --> 00:59:17.180
to let me go see a
doctor like Systrom who

00:59:17.180 --> 00:59:20.960
can do the tests to
actually measure my blood

00:59:20.960 --> 00:59:23.030
flow, and my heart
rate, and my blood

00:59:23.030 --> 00:59:25.490
pressure under
different circumstances,

00:59:25.490 --> 00:59:28.730
and hone in on what's
the exact cause in me

00:59:28.730 --> 00:59:30.626
because he's got
effective treatments.

00:59:39.600 --> 00:59:43.080
- So I wanted to ask more
broadly, we have about half

00:59:43.080 --> 00:59:46.152
of patients with POTS, and
chronic fatigue syndrome,

00:59:46.152 --> 00:59:46.860
and fibromyalgia.

00:59:46.860 --> 00:59:51.180
The syndromic disorders
have a tangible small fiber

00:59:51.180 --> 00:59:55.530
neuropathy, and you're
looking at the immunotherapy

00:59:55.530 --> 00:59:56.630
in these patients.

00:59:56.630 --> 00:59:57.270
Has anybody--

00:59:57.270 --> 00:59:58.020
- In some of them.

00:59:58.020 --> 00:59:59.580
- In some of these
patients, right.

00:59:59.580 --> 01:00:03.690
Has anybody looked for
functional receptor antibodies

01:00:03.690 --> 01:00:05.280
that maybe don't
cause a neuropathy,

01:00:05.280 --> 01:00:08.130
or haven't yet, at whatever
stage in the illness,

01:00:08.130 --> 01:00:12.300
doing like the passive transfer
work to rabbits or something,

01:00:12.300 --> 01:00:15.030
with serum from patients who
don't have the neuropathy

01:00:15.030 --> 01:00:17.340
to see if the immunological
profile you're finding

01:00:17.340 --> 01:00:19.770
might be in those patients too?

01:00:19.770 --> 01:00:23.160
- Yeah, we would always
use controlled sera,

01:00:23.160 --> 01:00:27.030
and so it's very important to
thank not only the patients who

01:00:27.030 --> 01:00:30.480
come for research, but
also the normal controls,

01:00:30.480 --> 01:00:34.920
and people with other diseases
because all of the work we do,

01:00:34.920 --> 01:00:38.520
we have to compare what we
find from patients to what we

01:00:38.520 --> 01:00:41.020
find in the general population.

01:00:41.020 --> 01:00:47.382
And so yes, we would always
use serum from non-patients

01:00:47.382 --> 01:00:49.090
to do these kinds of
experiments as well.

01:00:59.500 --> 01:01:02.800
- I had two observations
I'd like to share.

01:01:02.800 --> 01:01:09.850
It seems that the cause of
this problem is in the plasma,

01:01:09.850 --> 01:01:14.465
and that it's an
immunecomplex problem.

01:01:14.465 --> 01:01:19.360
There are immune antibodies
that are in the plasma.

01:01:19.360 --> 01:01:24.760
Has plasmapheresis been
considered as a treatment

01:01:24.760 --> 01:01:30.400
to remove the offending plasma,
and replace it with colloid,

01:01:30.400 --> 01:01:31.955
or clean plasma.

01:01:34.650 --> 01:01:39.230
Instead of infusing
immunoglobulin G

01:01:39.230 --> 01:01:42.920
to down regulate the
production of auto antibodies,

01:01:42.920 --> 01:01:46.580
perhaps plasmapheresis could
remove the offending agent.

01:01:50.720 --> 01:01:52.140
That's one observation.

01:01:52.140 --> 01:01:54.230
The other observation
I had was that--

01:01:54.230 --> 01:02:00.550
or question-- there's talk
about genetic involvement.

01:02:00.550 --> 01:02:07.420
Has consideration been given
to the abnormal gene sequences

01:02:07.420 --> 01:02:12.900
being viral inserts,
and not inherited

01:02:12.900 --> 01:02:15.680
from a prior infection?

01:02:15.680 --> 01:02:20.780
DNA from a particular
virus, enterovirus perhaps.

01:02:20.780 --> 01:02:25.940
So if it lies in the
genes, in that sense,

01:02:25.940 --> 01:02:30.110
that would account for the
chronicity of the illness,

01:02:30.110 --> 01:02:33.140
and that would account
for the remissions,

01:02:33.140 --> 01:02:38.740
and then the relapses
because the genes are still

01:02:38.740 --> 01:02:42.150
there expressing themselves.

01:02:42.150 --> 01:02:45.880
So I'm wondering-- I guess the
point is has consideration been

01:02:45.880 --> 01:02:49.820
given to the fact that
these might be gene inserts,

01:02:49.820 --> 01:02:52.110
not mutations, and
not inherited--

01:02:52.110 --> 01:02:53.370
- Great question.

01:02:53.370 --> 01:02:54.310
Great question.

01:02:54.310 --> 01:02:57.930
So actually, a couple of
questions and comments, and one

01:02:57.930 --> 01:03:00.630
is about other types
of immunotherapy.

01:03:00.630 --> 01:03:03.100
And again, immunotherapy
is only one treatment,

01:03:03.100 --> 01:03:07.560
and it's a treatment for
those people who it turns out

01:03:07.560 --> 01:03:10.710
we think have an autoimmune
cause, which is really not

01:03:10.710 --> 01:03:12.600
everybody.

01:03:12.600 --> 01:03:17.370
But for immunotherapy, you
have to think and individualize

01:03:17.370 --> 01:03:19.290
the treatment for the
different patients,

01:03:19.290 --> 01:03:21.750
and there are different
immunotherapies.

01:03:21.750 --> 01:03:24.100
There's no one size fits all.

01:03:24.100 --> 01:03:25.770
And so yes, absolutely.

01:03:25.770 --> 01:03:30.300
I do have some patients
who use plasma exchange.

01:03:30.300 --> 01:03:33.370
Taking out their own
blood-- it's like dialysis.

01:03:33.370 --> 01:03:36.990
It dialyzes away
their autoantibodies.

01:03:36.990 --> 01:03:39.750
But again, another
expensive therapy that's

01:03:39.750 --> 01:03:41.370
very hard to get approval for.

01:03:41.370 --> 01:03:44.190
It's got its own
problems, and so it's not

01:03:44.190 --> 01:03:46.410
something that is routine.

01:03:46.410 --> 01:03:51.700
We try to start with the
simpler, more mainstream

01:03:51.700 --> 01:03:52.590
immunotherapies.

01:03:52.590 --> 01:03:54.870
There's a whole host
of new immunotherapies

01:03:54.870 --> 01:03:56.610
that are coming to market.

01:03:56.610 --> 01:03:58.950
Eculizumab, for instance,
is newly approved

01:03:58.950 --> 01:04:01.350
for a neurologic
autoimmune indication.

01:04:01.350 --> 01:04:03.780
So it's really exciting
days, and that's

01:04:03.780 --> 01:04:08.220
why it's so important that basic
scientists get involved in this

01:04:08.220 --> 01:04:10.290
so that we can
actually figure out

01:04:10.290 --> 01:04:13.260
what the molecular
epitopes are, what

01:04:13.260 --> 01:04:17.100
the targets are of antibodies
because when we really

01:04:17.100 --> 01:04:20.010
know what's going on at
the molecular level, then

01:04:20.010 --> 01:04:22.830
we can use much more
targeted therapies.

01:04:22.830 --> 01:04:27.090
As you say, IVIg is kind of
a dirty drug that is a very

01:04:27.090 --> 01:04:28.590
crude way of approaching it.

01:04:28.590 --> 01:04:30.870
It's the best
treatment we have now,

01:04:30.870 --> 01:04:34.080
but I think as this
comes into sharper focus,

01:04:34.080 --> 01:04:38.520
and as other research teams
get involved beyond my own,

01:04:38.520 --> 01:04:41.460
it's going to open the door
to much better therapies.

01:04:41.460 --> 01:04:44.250
With regard to the genes,
the genes are involved.

01:04:44.250 --> 01:04:46.200
Without any question,
genes are involved

01:04:46.200 --> 01:04:47.460
in autoimmune diseases.

01:04:47.460 --> 01:04:50.370
We're interested in
looking at the HLA antigen.

01:04:50.370 --> 01:04:53.490
Some people have just
unknown genetic mutations.

01:04:53.490 --> 01:04:58.770
I was at NIH last week working
on a family with a novel very

01:04:58.770 --> 01:05:01.560
clear familial genetic
cause that's never been

01:05:01.560 --> 01:05:03.180
described in the literature.

01:05:03.180 --> 01:05:06.530
So by doing detailed
mapping of the genes

01:05:06.530 --> 01:05:08.550
from that family, the
affected individuals,

01:05:08.550 --> 01:05:10.500
the unaffected
individuals, we're

01:05:10.500 --> 01:05:14.160
likely going to discover a new
gene that causes neuropathy.

01:05:14.160 --> 01:05:16.950
But even in people who don't
have familial neuropathies,

01:05:16.950 --> 01:05:20.400
we know that tendencies
are genetically inherited.

01:05:20.400 --> 01:05:22.770
And so when we can
get our database up

01:05:22.770 --> 01:05:25.290
to the level of
tens of thousands

01:05:25.290 --> 01:05:28.170
of samples, right Gary?

01:05:28.170 --> 01:05:29.850
At that point,
then you can really

01:05:29.850 --> 01:05:36.782
start doing population genetics,
epigenetics, and much more

01:05:36.782 --> 01:05:37.740
sophisticated genetics.

